05204nam a22007575i 9780674287730DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20232022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742877307 a10.4159/97806742877302doi  a(DE-B1597)634185  a(OCoLC)1343104388  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJZ27.F67 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a327.73009/04223/eng/202206281 aAllen, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEvery Citizen a Statesman :bThe Dream of a Democratic Foreign Policy in the American Century /cDavid Allen. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2023] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Destiny and Democracy -- t1 “Foreign Relations Was Something for Women” -- t2 The Fact Cult -- t3 The War for Democracy -- t4 How to Teach a City to Lead the World -- t5 World Affairs Are Your Affairs -- t6 Who, Me? -- t7 The Diplomatic One Percent -- tEpilogue: A Foreign Policy for the American People? -- tAbbreviations -- tArchives -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe surprising story of the movement to create a truly democratic foreign policy by engaging ordinary Americans in world affairs.No major arena of US governance is more elitist than foreign policy. International relations barely surface in election campaigns, and policymakers take little input from Congress. But not all Americans set out to build a cloistered foreign policy “establishment.” For much of the twentieth century, officials, activists, and academics worked to foster an informed public that would embrace participation in foreign policy as a civic duty.The first comprehensive history of the movement for “citizen education in world affairs,” Every Citizen a Statesman recounts an abandoned effort to create a democratic foreign policy. Taking the lead alongside the State Department were philanthropic institutions like the Ford and Rockefeller foundations and the Foreign Policy Association, a nonprofit founded in 1918. One of the first international relations think tanks, the association backed local World Affairs Councils, which organized popular discussion groups under the slogan “World Affairs Are Your Affairs.” In cities across the country, hundreds of thousands of Americans gathered in homes and libraries to learn and talk about pressing global issues.But by the 1960s, officials were convinced that strategy in a nuclear world was beyond ordinary people, and foundation support for outreach withered. The local councils increasingly focused on those who were already engaged in political debate and otherwise decried supposed public apathy, becoming a force for the very elitism they set out to combat. The result, David Allen argues, was a chasm between policymakers and the public that has persisted since the Vietnam War, insulating a critical area of decisionmaking from the will of the people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aInternational relationsxCitizen participationxHistoryy20th century. 0aNon-state actors (International relations)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical participationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aCouncil on Foreign Relations.  aDemocracy and foreign policy.  aForeign Policy Association.  aForeign policy elite.  aFoundations and foreign policy.  aLeague of Women Voters.  aPublic opinion and foreign policy.  aU.S. foreign policy.  aWomen and foreign affairs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078579140uhttps: